    "The delta function insertions in (2.28) play a similar role and the discussion in [53] has some parallels with our discussion in section 5.2.",
    "An important difference is that the insertions in (2.28) are SL(2) invariant, whereas the insertions in [53] transform non-trivially under J -.",
    "We note also that the δ(S) insertions fulfill the role of background charges discussed around equation (2.23) above.The fact that this description is not restricted to a semi-classical limit will be an important point and will allow us to explain the somewhat unreasonable effectiveness of the Wakimoto representation in the literature.",
    "We should emphasise that, whilst the action S W may appear to describe a chiral theory, the insertions δ 2 (S a) encode information about the antiholomorphic sector.",
